<br>
Well, actually, it does affect nuking classes greatly.  The whole dps issue kicks in again with this.  If our mana pool is larger, then we can sustain a burn for longer.  Regen certainly has a role in this as well but with a larger mana pool at our command we can stay in a battle longer without having to med.<br>
<br>
And I don't thing that aggro is our limiting factor when it comes to casting.  I can just about over burn on critters without fear of dying due to being aggro'd.  Warrior taunts, enchanters mez, clerics and wizards can stun and root.  There are too many ways to govern aggro for it to be of a concern, at least for me.  I don't do a lot of damage because I'm always conscious of my mana.  Always trying to ensure that I don't have to skip pulls simply because I need to med through them.<br>
<br>
A larger mana pool will be of great importance when you are fighting creatures that have massive hitpoints and the battle is a lengthy one.  I fought Innoruuk the other day, yeah I know... generation 1 MoB, and I drained my mana completely with no aggro from him and I barely did any noticeable damage.  With a larger mana pool I can stay in the fight longer, even if it is just for one more cast.<br>
<br>
I can not see any balance issue reason for capping it.  Of course I don't have the warped view of balance that VI/SOE does.  If they want to cap mana then the least they should do is cap it at something higher than 500.  <br>
<br>
<br>
Maurley Deyesailot<br>
Lvl 56 Evoker<br>
